1460":"1460","1481":"1481","1490":"1490","Abt 1483":"about 1483","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1506":"about 1506","1506":"1506","1504":"from 11 January 1504 to 10 January 1505","Abt. 1480":"about 1480",", Leicester, Eng.":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","Croft, Leicestershire, England":"Croft, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llwyd","type":"LAST","meanings":["Same as Lhuyd, q v."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sybil Isabel Llwyd was born about 1483, her father, Sir Gruffydd Llwyd ap Rhys The Second Lord of Denorwig, was 24 and her mother, Gwenllian Verch Gryg, was 23. She married Sir William Robert Clements of Croft from 11 January 1504 to 10 January 1505, in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1483–":"umbes 1483–Surnud","1483–Female":"1483–Surnud","1481–1558":"1481–1558","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1460–1535":"1460–1535","1461–1490":"1461–1490","1461":"1461","1571":"1571","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1481":"1481","1490":"1490","Abt 1483":"umbes 1483","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","about 1506":"umbes 1506","1506":"1506","1504":"11. jaanuar 1504 kuni 10. jaanuar 1505","Abt. 1480":"umbes 1480",", Leicester, Eng.":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Croft, Leicestershire, England":"Croft, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1483–":"noin 1483–Kuollut","1483–Female":"1483–Kuollut","1481